[SN]TITLE[SN]
US stocks hit by worries over Greece and China

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
(Close): Wall Street was overshadowed by a technical glitch that caused trading on the New York Stock Exchange to be suspended for almost four hours.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
The main indexes were already in the red before the suspension, rattled by continuing falls in Chinese shares and concerns over the Greek debt crisis.
The Dow Jones closed 1.5% lower, or 261 points, to 17,515, while the S&P 500 shed 1.7%, or 34 points, at 2,046.
The tech-rich Nasdaq, 1.8% lower, or 87 points, ended at 4,909.
China's Shanghai Composite index fell a further 6% on Wednesday and is now down 30% from its June peak.
US-listed shares of Chinese firms came under pressure, with Alibaba down 2.1% and Baidu down 1.58%.
Microsoft shares eased 0.14% lower after it announced it was cutting 7,800 jobs, most of them in the struggling phone unit it bought from Nokia last year.
Tesla Motors fell 4.82% after a broker downgrade, the ratings cut in two days.
